Here is the complete CSS for your Angular Material Add/Edit popup form inside the exchange-rate component. This CSS will:

Ensure the Cancel and Save buttons are visible.

Match the layout to the FIS Data Integrity Manager UI style.

Fix issues with layout overflow, alignment, spacing, and dialog appearance.



---

✅ exchange-rate.component.css (or inline dialog style CSS)

/* Dialog container styling */
.mat-dialog-container {
  padding: 24px !important;
  border-radius: 8px;
  background-color: #ffffff;
  box-shadow: 0px 5px 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
}

/* Form layout inside popup */
.popup-form {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 16px;
  width: 100%;
  min-width: 400px;
  max-width: 600px;
}

/* Each row in form */
.form-row {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
}

/* Label styling */
.form-row label {
  flex: 1;
  font-weight: 600;
  margin-right: 12px;
  color: #333;
}

/* Input styling */
.form-row input,
.form-row select,
.form-row .mat-form-field {
  flex: 2;
  width: 100%;
}

.mat-form-field {
  width: 100%;
}

/* Footer buttons */
.popup-footer {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
  gap: 12px;
  padding-top: 24px;
  border-top: 1px solid #ccc;
  margin-top: 16px;
}

/* Button styling */
.popup-footer button {
  min-width: 90px;
  font-weight: 500;
}

/* Fix for overflowing dialog content */
mat-dialog-content {
  max-height: 400px;
  overflow-y: auto;
}

/* Optional: Calendar icon alignment */
.calendar-icon {
  cursor: pointer;
  margin-left: -32px;
  z-index: 10;
  position: relative;
}


---

✅ Matching HTML Structure

Here’s the expected HTML structure to work with this CSS:

<form class="popup-form">
  <div class="form-row">
    <label>From Currency</label>
    <mat-form-field appearance="outline">
      <mat-select [(value)]="data.fromCurr">
        <mat-option *ngFor="let curr of currencyList" [value]="curr">{{ curr }}</mat-option>
      </mat-select>
    </mat-form-field>
  </div>

  <div class="form-row">
    <label>To Currency</label>
    <mat-form-field appearance="outline">
      <mat-select [(value)]="data.toCurr">
        <mat-option *ngFor="let curr of currencyList" [value]="curr">{{ curr }}</mat-option>
      </mat-select>
    </mat-form-field>
  </div>

  <div class="form-row">
    <label>Rate</label>
    <mat-form-field appearance="outline">
      <input matInput type="number" [(ngModel)]="data.rate" name="rate" />
    </mat-form-field>
  </div>

  <div class="form-row">
    <label>Effective Date</label>
    <mat-form-field appearance="outline">
      <input matInput [matDatepicker]="picker" [(ngModel)]="data.lastMod" name="lastMod">
      <mat-datepicker-toggle matSuffix [for]="picker"></mat-datepicker-toggle>
      <mat-datepicker #picker></mat-datepicker>
    </mat-form-field>
  </div>

  <div class="popup-footer">
    <button mat-stroked-button (click)="onCancel()">Cancel</button>
    <button mat-flat-button color="primary" (click)="onSave()">Save</button>
  </div>
</form>


---

✅ Result

With this setup, your popup form will have:

A clean, professional layout

Clearly visible Cancel and Save buttons

Proper spacing and field alignment

Scrollable content if fields overflow



